### CP-2 Contingency Plan — Current Status

**Authorization condition status:** AT RISK — 90-day deadline in 12 days at Q1 reporting.

**Milestones completed:**
- Milestone 1: Downtime procedure outline drafted (ISSO)
- Milestone 2: IT restoration procedure documented and tested (ISSO + IT Administrator)

**Milestone 3 (AT RISK):** Clinical leadership review and approval meeting. Required participants: Health IT Manager (confirmed), Clinical Director (confirmed), Charge Nurse (not yet confirmed). Meeting scheduled; AO intervention requested to confirm Charge Nurse attendance.

**Milestone 4 (pending Milestone 3):** Final CP-2 document signed, distributed to all clinical staff, physical downtime cards posted at clinical workstations.

**What the complete CP-2 must contain that does not yet exist in documented form:**

The paper-based downtime encounter form — a one-page paper form that clinical staff can use to document an encounter when OpenMRS is unavailable. This form needs to capture: patient name and ID (from paper registration), date and time, presenting complaint, assessment and plan, medications ordered or dispensed, and the name of the clinician documenting. Without this form designed, reviewed by clinical staff for usability, printed, and physically available at clinical workstations, the downtime procedure is not operational.

The data reconciliation procedure — after OpenMRS is restored, how are paper downtime records entered into the system? Who is responsible for entry? What is the deadline for reconciliation? What happens if a paper record is illegible? This is the step that most contingency plans leave underdocumented.

The alternative communication procedure — if OpenMRS is unavailable because of a network or infrastructure failure that also affects email and internal communication, how do clinical staff notify each other of the outage and coordinate the downtime response? A physical notification path (charge nurse responsibility, front desk notification, posted downtime notice) needs to be documented alongside the IT restoration procedure.

