## The Connection Between IR, CP-2, and the Risk Register

Looking at the complete incident response and contingency planning section alongside the Day 89 risk register, two connections stand out:

**RS-004 (Ransomware, HIGH) depends most directly on IR and CP execution.** The risk is elevated. The technical controls are working. The residual risk reduction to MODERATE depends on: (1) the EC2 isolation playbook being executable by the IT Administrator without ISSO contact (IR-3 tabletop tests this), (2) the clinical downtime procedures being operational so that a ransomware-induced unavailability incident does not become a clinical care crisis (CP-2 completion closes this), and (3) the backup restoration being executable within RTO (Q1 test passed; M-003 optimization in progress). All three depend on demonstrated readiness, not just documented readiness.

**The AU-12 gap (denied access logging) affects both IR Playbook 1 and RS-005 detection.** The Compromised Credentials playbook's audit log review step is limited by the current AU-12 implementation gap. When the AU-12 remediation is complete, the playbook's forensic capability improves materially — denied access events that preceded the confirmed access event will be visible in the log, improving the ISSO's ability to reconstruct the attack timeline and scope the potential ePHI exposure.

