## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The 2am incident scenario — specifically the tabletop element where the IT Administrator cannot reach the ISSO — is directly informed by the **2020 Universal Health Services (UHS) ransomware attack**, which was one of the largest healthcare ransomware incidents on record.

The UHS attack began on a Sunday night. The initial response was delayed in part because the attack started during a weekend overnight shift, and the escalation path from the first responders to decision-making leadership took longer than it should have — the same dynamic as the OpenMRS 2am/unreachable-ISSO scenario.

The UHS case produced an extended recovery period affecting 400 hospitals and healthcare facilities across the US and UK. The clinical impact — staff reverting to paper records, delayed lab results, postponed procedures — was severe and extended because the response in the first hours did not execute as planned.

For the OpenMRS program, the UHS case justifies the specific design choice of pre-authorizing the IT Administrator to isolate the EC2 instance without ISSO approval. Waiting 15 minutes to reach the ISSO in a ransomware scenario allows the malware 15 additional minutes of propagation time. The pre-authorization removes that decision bottleneck while maintaining accountability through the mandatory 15-minute ISSO notification requirement.

